column16: What is your annual household income?
column17: What was your overall impression of this event (quality, lighting, sound, value)?
column18: Please share any other suggestions or ideas that would help us enhance your experience at Gesa Power House Theatre. If you would like someone to respond to your feedback, please include your contact information. Thank you!

column17: Although the volume was a little quiet for me in the back, I was in fact able to hear and found it to be a wonderful experience.
column18: I always drink water at the shows and feel bad about the bottles. Maybe a water cooler would be nice?

Totally enjoyed the event.
Thank you for offering this.

column17: Excellent film!  Sound quality was a little muddy and the screen seemed to be be a bit wavy, but not too bad.  And better to see this at your theater than on my computer or home TV.
column18:
I understand your preference for selling tickets in advance, but perhaps allow an option of not selecting seats? In this case the small-ish crowd ended up bunched together due to that requirement, and I was initially seated behind a really tall person. Luckily we were able to move down a few seats so I could see.
Also it looks like you are bringing more films to Gesa--great! I hope you'll send out emails about these.

column17: The documentary was fantastic, very interesting and the photography, spectacular.
column18: Nice staff and volunteers, thank you.

column17: very interesting film; no problems with showing; comfortable seating and viewing
The quality of the documentary chosen to air at the theatre was exceptional.  More of that please!  Lighting and sound were very acceptable.
column18: One had to pay strict attention to what was enveloping on the screen.  Based on the rate at which the photos played through, it was quite literally like fast film.  What a treasure of a story and collection of memories.  Extremely touching that one would unwrap themselves and their family's true history before an audience.  A good educational experience.
